article.description: Shareef Abdur-Rahim scored 29 points,  including the go-ahead jump shot with 2:42 left in overtime, to lift the Atlanta Hawks to a 100-94 victory over the Miami Heat.
article.headline: Hawks find their comfort zone ... in OT
article.linkText: Hawks rally from 11 down in fourth, then beat Heat in OT
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Hawks keep putting in for overtime.
Abdur-Rahim

Shareef Abdur-Rahim scored 29 points as the Hawks rallied from an 11-point deficit in the fourth quarter, then beat the Miami Heat 100-94 in overtime Friday night. The Hawks went beyond regulation for the third time in five games, including a double-overtime loss at Boston a week earlier. They have won two overtime games since then -- their only victories in the last six. "This is teaching us how to win close games,'' said Glenn Robinson, who scored 24 points for Atlanta. "We'll take wins however we can get them -- overtime, regulation, it doesn't matter.'' Atlanta wouldn't have needed overtime if not for Mike James, who hit a 3-pointer with 3.6 seconds left in regulation to tie the game at 88. But the Hawks recovered from that stunning shot once the extra period began. "You've got to stay tough,'' Abdur-Rahim said. "We had to erase that out of our minds real fast. You don't worry about it. It's a new game at that point.'' Abdur-Rahim put the Hawks ahead for good, 94-91, on a jumper with 2:41 remaining in the extra period, then Atlanta sealed the victory at the foul line. The Hawks made all eight free throws in overtime and finished 37-of-44 at the line. Miami, on the other hand, was 18-of-24, failing to take advantage of 22 offensive rebounds. "We can't finish anything,'' moaned coach Pat Riley, whose team has won just three of 15 games. Jason Terry also had 24 points for Atlanta. Malik Allen scored 21 and Eddie Jones 20 to lead the Heat, which shot just 35 percent (36-of-103) from the field. "Atlanta had a defense down the stretch,'' Jones said. "We're not making our shots. We have wide-open shots, but they're not falling. When they start falling, we'll be OK.'' The Hawks looked listless in the opening minutes of the fourth, falling behind 77-66 when James hit a 3 with 10:22 remaining. But Atlanta turned up the defensive pressure, limiting the offense-challenged Heat to just 3-of-13 shooting the rest of the period. "It was do-or-die,'' Terry said. "We knew every possession, every second counted. For some reason, they were getting a lot of long rebounds. Fortunately, we started getting our bodies on people.'' Atlanta finally went ahead when Terry stole a pass from Jones, took off the other way and was fouled by Travis Best on the drive to the basket. Terry made both free throws to put the Hawks ahead 84-83 with 1:55 remaining. Robinson worked the pick-and-roll with Terry and hit a 10-foot jumper to put the Hawks ahead 86-85 with 44 seconds remaining. After Jones missed a baseline jumper, Ira Newble made a couple of free throws with 10.7 seconds left to give the Hawks a three-point cushion. James took care of that. After a pick knocked off defender Emanual Davis, the Heat guard swished a 3-pointer from the top of the key over Darvin Ham. On a frenetic final play of regulation, Brian Grant stole the inbounds pass, then had a pass picked off by Terry, who managed to get off a desperation shot from just inside halfcourt. It nearly went in, bouncing off the backboard and front of the rim. After Miami scored the first seven points of the game, the Hawks were poised to pull away in the second quarter. They stretched their lead to 37-28 on a layup by Abdur-Rahim with 5:56 left in the half. But the Heat outscored the Hawks 14-6 down the stretch to close to 47-46 at the break.

Game notes
Just before the game, the Heat activated F Sean Lampley from the injured list. He had not played since an Oct. 22 exhibition game because of a sprained left foot. Miami replaced Lampley on the injured list with little-used rookie C Ken Johnson. He's been bothered by tendinitis in his left knee, playing only 2 minutes in five games this season. ... James beat the buzzer on baskets to end both the second and third quarters. Officials reviewed both plays, with the replays showing that he got off the shots in time. ... Atlanta F Dion Glover didn't play for the first time since missing the first two games of the season with a sprained ankle. Hawks coach Lon Kruger said it was simply a coaching decision, prompted by Davis' strong defensive play.
